Gordon Parks, Boy with June Bug, Fort Scott Kansas, 1963

Parks (1912-2006) was a self-taught artist who became the first African American photographer for Life and Vogue magazines. 

He purchased his first camera at the age of 25 after viewing photographs of migrant workers in a magazine. His early fashion photographs caught the attention of Marva Louis, wife of the boxing champion Joe Louis, who encouraged Parks to move to a larger city. In 1969 (at the age of 57), Parks became the first African American to direct a major Hollywood movie, the film adaptation of The Learning Tree. He wrote the screenplay and composed the score for the film.

Parks's next film, Shaft, was one of the biggest box-office hits of 1971. Isaac Hayes won an Academy Award for the movie's theme song. Parks also directed a 1972 sequel, Shaft's Big Score.

Image courtesy and copyright Gordon Parks
Foundation @gordonparksfoundation

For more information on this work contact @weinsteinhammons Gallery

Hi! I’m Lindsay Bottos and I’ll be posting some of my work throughout this coming week!I’m a Baltimore-based multidisciplinary artist whos endeavors primarily revolve around the mediums of analog photography, video, and writing. My artistic practice is deeply rooted in personal experiences, particularly within interpersonal relationships, and the profound impact of the digital and social media era.

One of my most notable projects, “Anonymous,” garnered significant attention in 2014. In this project, I presented Apple Photobooth self-portraits layered with unsolicited comments and messages I had received online on top. Notable news outlets including Good Morning America, Huffington Post, and the Baltimore Sun have reported on the project. It was written that the project sparked a lot of essential dialogue surrounding the pervasive issues of harassment and the objectification of women online.

My fine art work has also found a home in esteemed and international galleries including my local favorite @currentspace , and it has been featured in prominent publications such as the Baltimore Sun, Glamour and Seventeen. 

In my professional career, I’m always filling various roles, including fine artist, freelance photographer, prop stylist, and creative director for photo and video productions.

Here is a collection of some of my favorite self portraits I’ve taken through recent years. Most are taken with 35mm film with the exception of the B+W mini film photobooth pics and the crispest one featuring my fujifilm X100V which is digital.

I’m super excited to take over to share my work with you all this week!

[Amended] Digital Art by Steve McGhee, 2009 

This Image was popularized by a misleading ad on Yahoo titled, "These Mistakes Had Catastrophic Consequences” and has been used by many reputable websites as purportedly showing the last moments of Air Florida Flight 90. According to BoredPanda, the illustration was created by a Canadian graphic designer named Steve McGhee. The website described McGhee's work as "depicting catastrophic events such as planes crashing, cities destroyed by tsunamis, aliens invading, and other end-of-the-world scenarios."

Original Caption: Air Florida Flight 90 Crash, 1982

On January 13, 1982, Air Florida Flight 90, a Boeing Model 737-200 series airplane, crashed shortly after takeoff from Washington National Airport (now Reagan National Airport), Washington, D.C. The plane experienced difficulty in climbing immediately following rotation and subsequently stalled. Around two minutes after takeoff, the Boeing 737-222 registered as N62AF crashed into the 14th Street Bridge over the Potomac River, striking seven occupied vehicles and plummeting into the Potomac. Four passengers and one flight attendant were rescued; four motorists on the bridge were killed.

The Analog Film Photography Association presents artist of the month Lindsay Bottos' series of abstract film photographs; Incidental. 

Artist Statement: Incidental is an ongoing series that originated in 2011 as a curated collection of unintended yet evocative outcomes derived from shooting and processing 35mm film. Archivism is integral to my practice and artistic approach, serving as the catalyst for the inception of this visual anthology. These unaltered and serendipitous photographs encompass a diverse array of methodologies, including the utilization of long-expired film, the accidental introduction of moisture and environmental elements onto film prior to processing, variations in film chemistry during the development process, as well as light leaks stemming from malfunctioning cameras, improper film handling, and even the inclusion of end frames traditionally omitted from scanning. The trajectory of this project is indefinite, as I aspire to continue it throughout the course of my lifetime.

These are just a few selections from the show. Incidental will be on view on the AFPA website and an artist book will be available soon.

Teenagers In Their Bedrooms, Adrienne Salinger, 1984-6

Post 1/2

"It was 1984, and I was in my early 20s. I went up to strangers in malls and on the streets, or in women's restrooms - wherever teenagers tend to congregate.
I would meet one person at a time and ask if I could come home with them and photograph them. Even when I was doing it, it was strange. I photographed maybe 60 people, up and down the west coast. I spent all day with them, bringing large equipment into rooms that were 12 feet by 12 feet. And listening to their stories.

I was trying hard to address the way that people define themselves, to somehow allow coming of age to be scrutinised in a way that defied cliche. Before then, I felt strongly that the only images that existed of teenagers were from an adult's perspective, and the power differential bothered me. As viewers, we look at a picture and immediately reduce it to a one-liner as fast as we can. Our own shit comes up instantly. But I realised the teenagers had a clarity on their points of view that hadn't yet been damaged by compromise.

When you're a teenager, you're trying on identities continually. But you change so quickly that the things you have are all contradictions of themselves.
Later, when we're adults, we spend a lot of time trying to carve a consistent, coherent identity. We somehow get the impression that being an adult means everything lines up, right? But really, the only thing that makes us interesting at all is the way that doesn't happen. Adults hide a lot of shit in the closet. But a teenager only has that 12 by 12 feet.
Everything has to fit in there: the past and the future.

Everybody's got their stuffed animals, even when I was photographing teens smoking weed and talking about drugs and sex." 

- Interview from Dazed, F/W 2015

Announcing the release of Incidental by Lindsay Bottos ✨ Unintended film images from 2011 - Present

“Incidental” is an ongoing series that originated in 2011 as a curated collection of unintended outcomes derived from shooting and processing 35mm film. This is the first selection of images from the series available in print, featuring 45 pages of strange and dreamy abstract photographs. Printed at 6x9” on high quality archival paper with a flexible high gloss cover, this video just shows a small preview of the book.

That end of fall mood… Maybe it’s that full moon in gemini, maybe the cold, the rain, the grey. Last week, the city cut down the hundred year old linden tree in front of my house because a dead branch broke the window of my car in a storm. I feel like i’m similarly being punished, for being unfortunate enough to live and exist in a place too precarious for me, never really meant for me. Placed without much thought to simply make things nice, but ultimately disposable; for it is not possible to make everything better and everyone happy all of the time.

These photos are just from a somber walk through the park early on a foggy morning a year or so ago but I think of them sometimes. I took them with my #fujifilmx100v that i was fortunate enough to purchase when it first came out, but I’ve been considering selling it now that the value has doubled even though i love it, maybe another metaphor in there too…
